  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "For images forming further from the Einstein Radius, and particularly for large mass systems where the dark matter fraction is higher at the Einstein radius, the scatter is much smaller and can be less than the intrinsic scatter of a Type Ia SN.",
    "Foxley-Marrable et al. (2018) found that 20 percent of lensed SNe will contain an image with scatter comparable to the intrinsic scatter of a Type Ia supernova luminosity, assuming the dark matter fractions of elliptical galaxies derived in Auger et al. (2010) and a Saltpeter IMF.",
    "However, these standardisable images only form far beyond the Einstein radius of the lens.",
    "This means that the counter images are very close to the centre of the lens and demagnified.",
    "Measuring time delays will therefore be challenging, although the faint images arrive second so follow-up with a larger telescope may ameliorate this problem."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Foxley-Marrable et al. (2018) found that 20 percent of lensed SNe will contain an image with scatter comparable to the intrinsic scatter of a Type Ia supernova luminosity, assuming the dark matter fractions of elliptical galaxies derived in Auger et al. (2010) and a Saltpeter IMF."
  ]
